Identification of Causes by Patient Factor Regarding TP53 Mutations in Lung Cancer

Migyeong Moon, 2020140439, Food Bioscience and Technology, Korea University

1. Introduction

One of the most common mutations in human cancer is a somatic mutation in the TP53 gene (Olivier et al., 2010). TP53 mutations have a negative correlation with MAPK pathways that are deeply related to cancer. In addition, these mutations are positively associated with DNA replication, DNA topology regulation, and DNA damage response (Chen et al., 2020). This positive correlation of TP53 mutations corresponds with known synthetic interactions (Yeo et al., 2016), which provides information on the regulations of critical pathways in lung cancers by TP53. Therefore, this report focuses on the genetic alterations associated with the TP53 mutations. The genes positively related to TP53 mutations are shown in the following figure (Chen et al., 2020).

This report aims to identify patient factors associated with the TP53 mutations in a cohort of Taiwan. Among the genes related to TP53, we will investigate the cell cycle genes, which appear to be closely associated with the TP53 mutations in the figure above. Then using datasets, we will plot the relationship between the genomic alterations positively correlated with TP53 mutation and the patient factor. After the figures, the distinct characteristics of patients and genetic mutations of cell cycle genes will be discussed.

2. Setting Data Frame

# read data
library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(readxl)
read_excel("1-s2.0-S0092867420307431-mmc1.xlsx", sheet=2) -> patient_dat

read_excel("1-s2.0-S0092867420307431-mmc1.xlsx", sheet=6, na="NA") -> protein_dat

In the dataset, females, and non-smokers account for most of the samples. Therefore, this report will analyze data by limiting them to females and non-smokers to minimize the impact of factors other than the specific patient factors.

The information to be used in the three data frames is as follows.

In patient_dat, patient ID, gender, age, smoking status, Primary Tumor Location.

In mut_dat, the presence of TP53 mutations.

In mRNA_dat, mRNA expression data of genes positively correlated with TP53 mutations.

In protien_dat, protemoic expression data of gens positively correlated with TP53 mutations.

A. Manipulating patient_dat

First, the columns of patient_dat are as follows.

colnames(patient_dat)
[1] "ID"                     "Proteome_Batch"        
[3] "Gender"                 "Age"                   
[5] "Smoking Status"         "Histology Type"        
[7] "Stage"                  "EGFR_Status"           
[9] "Primary Tumor Location"

patient_dat is a dataframe about the patient’s basic information. Using select function, let’s extract only the information mentioned earlier.

patient_dat<- patient_dat %>%
  select(-("Histology Type":"EGFR_Status"),-"Proteome_Batch")

B. Manipulating mut_dat

mut_dat is a data frame about gene mutation information. Unlike patient_dat, mut_dat has a patient ID in the row, so it must be modified to appear as a column. First, in mut_dat, the existing column name does not match the content, so column 1 is designated as the column name instead. Second, let’s extract only the information we will use. Next, TP53 is extracted from genes using filter function because only mutations in the TP53 gene, not other genes, will be used in the data frame. Then, the patient ID is displayed in columns using the pivot_longer function. Finally, first column of the dataset is the same information as TP53, so it is removed.

names(mut_dat) <- mut_dat[1,] # 1st step
Warning: The `value` argument of `names<-` must be a character vector as of tibble 3.0.0.
mut_dat <- mut_dat[-1,] %>%
  select(-c("COUNT", "%")) %>% # 2nd step
  filter(Gene=="TP53") %>% # 3rd step
  pivot_longer(cols=-Gene, names_to="ID", values_to="TP53_mut") %>% # 4th step
  select(c("ID", "TP53_mut"))

C. Manipulating mRNA_dat

mRNA_dat is a data frame containing mRNA expression information of genes. Like mut_dat, the patient ID is displayed in a row in mRNA_dat. Therefore, it is expressed as a column using the pivot_longer function. In addition, the information to be used is the cell cycle genes positively associated with the TP53 mutations, so only information about those genes is extracted using the filter function.

The genes to be found in mRNA_dat are as follows. MCM2, MCM3, MCM4, MCM5, MCM6, MCM7, PCNA.

mRNA_dat <- mRNA_dat %>%
  select(-c("ensembl_gene_id", "Median"))%>% # Columns 2 and 3 are not required.
  filter(gene %in% c("MCM2", "MCM3", "MCM4", "MCM5", "MCM6", "MCM7", "PCNA")) %>% # we will use only the data about cell cycle genes.
  pivot_longer(cols=-gene, names_to="ID", values_to="mRNA_exp")

D. Manipulating protein_dat

protein_dat is a data frame including protein expression information of a gene. The configuration of the dataset is similar to that of mRNA_dat. Then, let’s follow the same steps of mRNA_dat.

protein_dat <- protein_dat %>%
  select(-"Accession") %>% # column1 is not required.
  filter(Gene %in% c("MCM2", "MCM3", "MCM4", "MCM5", "MCM6", "MCM7", "PCNA")) %>% # we will use only the data about cell cycle genes.
  pivot_longer(cols=-c("Gene", "Protein"), names_to="ID", values_to="Protein_exp")

F. Merging the dataframes

The data frames previously manipulated are integrated into two data frames called “total_mRNA” and “total_protein”. In this process, information is combined based on the patient ID. Also since we will only use data from females, non-smokers, let’s modify the data using filter function.

# Create total_mRNA using patient_dat, mut_dat, and mRNA_dat
total_mRNA<- merge(patient_dat, mut_dat, by="ID") %>%
  merge(mRNA_dat, by="ID")  %>%
  filter(Gender=="Female", `Smoking Status`=="Nonsmoke")

# Create total_protein, using patient_dat, mut_dat, protein_dat
total_protein<- merge(patient_dat, mut_dat, by="ID") %>%
  merge(protein_dat, by="ID") %>%
  filter(Gender=="Female", `Smoking Status`=="Nonsmoke")

To distinguish between people who have TP53 mutations and those who do not, let’s create new data frames called TP53_mRNA, non_mRNA, TP53_protein, and non_protein.

TP53_mRNA<- total_mRNA %>% filter(!is.na(TP53_mut))
non_mRNA<- total_mRNA %>% filter(is.na(TP53_mut))
TP53_protein <- total_protein %>% filter(!is.na(TP53_mut))
non_protein <- total_protein %>% filter(is.na(TP53_mut))

3. Visualization

library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)

A. Figure 1.

Figure 1 shows the expression of the cell cycle genes associated with the TP53 mutations according to age. First, samples of patients with TP53 mutation and those who do not in females and non-smokers are shown separately. Also, since this report aims to investigate the causes of lung cancer regarding TP53 mutations, I try to examine the correlation between cell cycle gene expression and patient factors using regression model lines. However, the figure do not show TP53 mutant patients aged 65 or older because of a lack of data.

# Make a plot about the expressions of mRNA by age
mRNA_age <- non_mRNA %>% group_by(gene) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Age, y=mRNA_exp)) +
  geom_point(data=TP53_mRNA, shape=15, color="#FC4E07") +
  geom_smooth(data=TP53_mRNA, method="lm", color="#FC4E07") +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, color="darkgrey") +
  theme_bw()+
  facet_wrap(~ gene) +
  labs(x = "Age",
       y = "mRNA expression",
       title = "mRNA")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Make a plot about the expressions of protein by age
protein_age <- non_protein %>% group_by(Gene) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Age, y=Protein_exp)) +
  geom_point(data=TP53_protein, shape=15, color="#00AFBB") +
  geom_smooth(data=TP53_protein, method="lm", color="#00AFBB") +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, color="darkgrey") +
  theme_bw()+
  facet_wrap(~ Gene) +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Proteomic expression", title = "Protein")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Make a multiple plot
figure1 <- plot_grid(mRNA_age, protein_age)
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
title <- ggdraw() + draw_label("Expression of Cell cycle Genes related TP53 mutations by Age", fontface='bold')
figure1 <- plot_grid(title, figure1, ncol=1, rel_heights = c(1,10))

# Save the plot
ggsave(figure1, file="./figure1.png", width=80, height=50, units=c("cm"))

B. Figure 2.

Figure 2 shows the cell cycle gene expression associated with the TP53 mutations according to the Primary tumor location. Data from TP53 mutant patients are displayed using box plots to investigate each step’s expression amount. In addition, the entire patient’s data is also marked with dots, and I try to test it compared to the TP53 mutation cases. In addition, Figure 2 can not be displayed for RML, RUL due to a lack of data.

# Make a plot about the expressions of mRNA by location
mRNA_location <- non_mRNA %>% group_by(gene) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`Primary Tumor Location`, y=mRNA_exp)) +
  geom_boxplot(data=TP53_mRNA,alpha=0.5, shape=15, color="#FC4E07") +
  geom_jitter(alpha=0.5, color="darkgrey") +
  theme_bw()+
  facet_wrap(~ gene) +
  labs(x = "Primary Tumor Location",
       y = "mRNA expression",
       title = "mRNA") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Make a plot about the expressions of mRNA by location
protein_location <- non_protein %>% group_by(Gene) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`Primary Tumor Location`, y=Protein_exp)) +
  geom_boxplot(data=TP53_protein,alpha=0.5, shape=15, color="#00AFBB") +
  geom_jitter(alpha=0.5, color="darkgrey") +
  theme_bw()+
  facet_wrap(~ Gene) +
  labs(x = "Primary Tumor Location",
       y = "Proteomic expression",
       title = "Protein") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Make a multiple plot
figure2 <- plot_grid(mRNA_location, protein_location)
title <- ggdraw() + draw_label("Expression of Cell cycle Genes related TP53 mutations by Location", fontface='bold')
figure2 <- plot_grid(title, figure2, ncol=1, rel_heights = c(1,10))

# Save the plot
ggsave(figure2, file="./figure2.png", width=80, height=50, units=c("cm"))

4. Discussion

First, the relationship between the cell cycle genes and age shown in Figure 1 showed similar expression tendencies for the 40s- 60s patients. In the case of MCM2 and MCM7 genes, patients with TP53 mutations tended to decrease with age. However, MCM2 and MCM7 genes were not related to TP53 mutations because TP53 mutant-free patients also tended to fall. Therefore, the age-dependent effect was considered insignificant in the case of the cell cycle gene associated with the TP53 mutation. Likewise, the expressions of proteins were found to be not related to age. TP53 mutant patients and non-mutant patients show the same tendency with age.

Next, there were differences between patients with and without TP53 mutations in the relationship shown in Figure 2. When the location of the primary tumor was RLL, mRNA expression of the MCM2 gene was very high in the presence of the TP53 mutation. In addition, the PCNA gene was also highly expressed. Also, when the location was LUL, there were differences between the patients in expressions of mRNA of MCM2, MCM4, and MCM5 genes. In other cases, the median value was higher than patients without TP53 mutation, but there were many overlapping areas. The results differed in the expressions of proteins. When the location was LLL, there was a significant gap between TP53 mutant and non-mutant patients in all cell cycle genes. In other cases, there was no big difference, so it was found that the expressions of the proteins were not related to the locations.

In conclusion, Figure 1 showed that cell cycle gene expression in patients with TP53 mutation is not significantly affected by age. In the case of the location of the primary tumor, it is thought that the site partially affects the cell cycle genes. Figure 2 shows the difference in expressions of mRNA between TP53 mutant and non-mutant patients when the locations are RLL or LUL. However, there were significant differences in proteomic expressions only when the locations were LLL. Therefore, it is thought that there were differences in expressions of cell cycle genes due to regulations in translation or post-translation modification step.

It was impossible to analyze elderly patients with TP53 mutations due to a lack of data. In addition, the locations of the primary tumor were limited in that only some types. I expect the relationship between the patient factor and the TP53 mutation-related genes to be clearly identified by supplementing and analyzing the data again.
